Drusus forced what is now known as the Brenner pass, meeting and overthrowing the Rhaetians in the valley near Tridentum, now Trent. In the meantime, or as soon as Drusus' success was assured, Tiberius was detached from Augustus' army in Gaul, with the purpose of taking the enemy in the rear. He ascended the Rhine valley to the Lake of Constance, where he launched a flotilla of boats‚ and entering at once several of the valleys which open on the lake, ‘penetrated the gorges of the Upper Rhine and Inn in every direction, so that at the conclusion of a brilliant and rapid campaign, the two brothers had effected the complete subjugation of the country of the Grisons and the Tyrol.' ‘The free tribes of the Eastern Alps appear then for the first time in history, only to disappear again for a thousand years.'
